@NODE "Mail_1" " Re: ReadArgs() [was Hi there] "
From: Alexander Niven-Jenkins <anj@cremlinsoftware.org>
Date: 10-01-00 10:16:09
Subject: @{b}Re: ReadArgs() [was Hi there]@{ub}

Hiya Gareth,

On 01-Oct-00, you wrote:

>>  /* Note nasty cast here - but at least it's only one! */
>>  if(myrdargs=ReadArgs(MYTEMPLATE,(long *)&myargs,NULL))

> That IS a complicated condition! Now, if I am following that correctly,
> that means "If 'myrdargs', which is the result of executing ReadArgs()
> using MYTEMPLATE as... well, the template, is blank (NULL) then carry on
> going?

   This is a great example of what must be the best thing C/C++ does.  In
C/C++ unlike nearly all (if not all other languages) every single
expression will evaluate to true or false.  ALL expressions.

   So what the above is saying if you split it up is the following (as you
have to in another language)...

   myrdargs = ReadArgs( MYTEMPLATE, ( long* )&myargs, NULL )
   if( myrdargs != NULL )
   {
      // code here
   }

   As far as the != NULL thing is you can ignore this, in C/C++ you can do:

   if( myrdargs )

   is the same as

   if( myrdargs != NULL )

   or

   if( !myrdargs )

   is the same as

   if( myrdargs == NULL )

   But as you can see from the above example, you can start joing them all
up, wonderful :-)  Although as you've noticed it can get complicated to
sort out!

Kind regards...

Alex
