On Mon, Oct 02, 2000 at 10:24:50AM +0100, Gareth Griffiths wrote:
> How do I use this? I tried it in a similar way to BASIC and it overwrote my
> original string with the uppercase version. Is it possible to temporarily
> turn it into uppercase in order to compare it against arguments passed to
> the executable?

  strupr() is non-standard function. Some compilers might provide it, but
  some don't. If this particular function modifies its argument, you must
  pass a writable copy of the original string.

> I would like to do a for() loop to check through the arguments one by one,
> but ideally I want to check for "AARDVARK" because some people might type it
> in with mixed case. Is this possible?

  If all you want is matching strings you should use "stricmp" (sometimes
  also called "strcasecmp") or better Stricmp from utility.library.

> At the moment I'm using the original, non-ReadArgs() method of doing this.
> Will ReadArgs() let me do it?

  AFAIK, ReadArgs() is not case-sensitive, therefore the spelling of a
  keyword on the commandline doesn't matter.

  Gunther

