Hi!

On Fri, 6 Oct 2000, Bippy M wrote:

> So below is a C Declaration can someone please explain what is happening?
> 
> void life(int, int *, int *, int *);
> 
> What I'd like to know is why are the * alone? and not set like say *help  ?
>

I'm going to guess that this is actually a function prototype, which is a
way of telling the compiler what types of parameters to expect when it
sees calls to the function later on.

In function prototypes, the parameter names are not required (though I
always put them anyway).   "int *" means a pointer to an int, which is all
the compiler really needs to know when calling the function.  You could
just as easily have:

void life(int foo, int *bar, int *asdf, int *qwer);

and the compiler would be just as happy.  However, you would probably be
happy, becuase you would have a better idea what is going on.  :-)
 
> right just so I have a basic understanding before I go and rash my miggy..
> are the following assumptions correct?
> 
> &AA returns the address which AA resides at (eg $4567)
> *AA returns the contents of memory location $4567
> 

Um, not quite.  &AA is correct.  However, *AA only works if AA is a
pointer type.  Let me try a quick, concrete example:

int   a;
int * b;

a = 4;    /* a is 4 */
b = &a;   /* b now points to a, contains like $4567)

so, if you look at b, you'll get the pointer value, if you look at *b,
you'll get 4.  *a would be an error.


