On 07-Oct-00, Bippy M wrote:
> Hiya Guys,
> I am a total beginner when it comes to C, I can however program blitz
> (To a degree)..
> Anyway I have been looking at pointers and cannot fully understand
> them.. I understand the theory behind them, i just don't follow it
> all!


Ok, in C the '*' operator has 3 meanings, it depend where you use it.

Here is the thing that get most beginners.

#In a declaration block only,# global or otherwise...
 * only means POINTER,   
so: BYTE * AA;  is a declaration for a 32 bit variable, 
like a ulong, that contains the address of something...

BYTE * AA means:  
    Declare a 32 bit pointer to point to data of type BYTE.


#In the body of a function #or macro or equate.
1:    3 * 4 = 12   as in multiply.....       
2:    (*AA) =  what is at the address pointed to by AA.

> &AA returns the address which AA resides at (eg $4567)
&AA is the ADDRESS of the variable AA, which may be anything,
a structure, a string (byte array), a word, a functions address, 
or even the actual address of the pointer to something,
(not what it points to)

> *AA returns the contents of memory location $4567
( * AA)  if AA is an initialized pointer, 
( * AA) points to the first entry
at the location (or address) that AA points to...

If AA is a string pointer (byte array pointer),
then if that string pointer is initialised to point to "WXYZ"
then (*AA) points to the letter 'W'.

> if I am incorrect can someone explain where I am going wrong!
Close.....  but you're thinking in assembler....


Try this:
----------

UBYTE *AA;
UBYTE string[]="WXYZ";
{
  AA = string;  
  AA ++;
  puts( AA );
}

or try this......
-----------

UBYTE *AA;
UBYTE string[]="WXYZ";
{
  AA = &string[0]; 
  AA ++;
  puts( AA );
}  

or this.....
------------

UBYTE *AA;
UBYTE string[]="WXYZ";
{
  AA = &string[1]; 
  puts( AA );
}  


