@NODE "Mail_74" " Re: optimising code "
From: Stephen Illingworth <gumshoe@firewall.co.uk>
Date: 10-11-00 16:31:20
Subject: @{b}Re: optimising code@{ub}

Hello Andrew

On 10-Oct-00, you wrote:

>
> Although, I've actually been playing around with it myself.  It's
> about 1 vbl faster now, but I'm sure theres room for improvement
> somewhere :)
>
>

These ideas may  not  make  any  difference if you use a good compiler with
optimization  turned on.  Nonetheless, optimizing compilers will always err
on  the  side  of caution if an optimization is unclear, so there is little
harm  in  doing  the  job  for  it  (or  at  least  nudging it in the right
direction.)




Sometimes  the checking of loop conditions can take a significant amount of
time, especially with large loops.  For example, in this portion of code,

    while(ox < fx){
        p=a[ox];
        if(p>0){b[ox]=p;}
        ox++;
    }

if  you can guarentee that fx will always be a multiple of some number, for
example, 4.  You can "unroll the loop".  For example,


    while(ox < fx){
        p=a[ox];
        if(p>0){b[ox]=p;}
        ox++;
        p=a[ox];
        if(p>0){b[ox]=p;}
        ox++;
        p=a[ox];
        if(p>0){b[ox]=p;}
        ox++;
        p=a[ox];
        if(p>0){b[ox]=p;}
        ox++;
    }

In  this  case,  the  expression  ox<fx is only executed 4 times (if fx=16)
rather than 16 times.

Of  course,  if  the size of your arrays are fixed, then you can unroll the
entire  loop.   If  they can take many sizes, but the sizes are known, then
consider  checking  for  those sizes and execute the appropriate (unrolled)
code.   A  variant  of  this  idea is to have the general case, as you have
already coded (with some unrolling), and to have special cases for the more
common sizes.

The  downside  of  loop unrolling is that the code may no longer fit in the
instruction  cache  of  the  processor - consider having different code for
different  processors,  thus  allowing  you  to  have  deeper unrolling for
processors with more cache.




With respect to this portion of code.

    p=a[ox];
    if(p>0){b[ox]=p;}

Indexing an array generally takes less time than an assignment.  So in this
case, the following /may/ be better.

    if (a[ox]>0){b[ox] = a[ox];}

and then p=a[ox] after the loops, if the calling function requires it.

In  addition,  if we remember that ox++ is actually an assignment, then the
following /may/ prove faster than the previous unrolled while() loop.

    while(ox < fx){
        if (a[ox]>0){b[ox] = a[ox];}
        if (a[ox]>0){b[ox+1] = a[ox+1];}
        if (a[ox]>0){b[ox+2] = a[ox+2];}
        if (a[ox]>0){b[ox+3] = a[ox+3];}
        ox+=4;
    }

...but don't bet on it :-)




In your outer loop

    for(oy=sy;oy<fy;oy++)

you  are  counting upwards.  If you can recode this so that the termination
test converges to 0, then it will be easier (and quicker) for the processor
to  check  for termination.  (I do appreciate however, that this may not be
possible in the example you have presented.)



Although  the  following  idea won't make any difference if the function is
called only once in a while, if it is itself part of a loop then altering,

    if(x<0){
        sx=-x;
        if(x<-15){return;}
    }
    if(y<0){
        sy=-y;
        if(y<-15){return;}
    }
    if(x>304){
        fx=320-x;
        if(x>319){return;}
    }
    if(y>224){
        fy=224-y;
        if(y>239){return;}
    }

to

    if(x<0){
        sx=-x;
        if(x<-15){return;}
    }
    else
    if(x>304){
        fx=320-x;
        if(x>319){return;}
    }

    if(y<0){
        sy=-y;
        if(y<-15){return;}
    }
    else
    if(y>224){
        fy=224-y;
        if(y>239){return;}
    }

/may/ offer some return.



Regards

Steve


