time, perhaps even with some unrolling of the loop, e.g.:

   ULONG *src = (ULONG *)s, *dst = (ULONG *)d;
   UWORD len = (320 >> 2) / 4;
   while(len--)
   {
      *dst++ = *src++;
      *dst++ = *src++;
      *dst++ = *src++;
      *dst++ = *src++;
   }

If speed is important then write the above in assembler, cause StormC
seems unable to use the dbra/dbf instruction (btw: the memcpy
implementation may also try to optimize the copy to longwords if
possible, depending on the implementation).

If you do switch to assembler then you may want to experiment with
'movem.l'. I recall on the A500 that the fastest way to clear a buffer
(apart from reading in an empty sector from disk ;-) ) was to clear all
registers but one and then have A6 point to the end of the buffer and do
a lot of "movem.l D0-A5,-(A6)" (clearing 56 bytes pr. instruction). But
IIRC the 68010+ features a special cache for one line loops, so here it
became faster with a simple "clr.l (A0)+" followed by "dbra D0,.loop".

