VBCC is pretty straight forward. Once you`ve installed it run the init_vbcc
command in a shell.  
The basic command line is just:

vc source-file-pattern -o output-file

Other useful command options you`ll probably need are:

-Ipathname     instructs the compiler to search pathname for include files in 
                   addition to the defaults.
-lLib          link with library Lib in addition to the defaults. 
-+             allow C++ (//) comments.
-O1            Set the optimisation level to 1. Can be set to 2 and 3 also but
                  your code may well become unstable.

If you want to compile WOS code use the +warpos option (once you`ve installed
the WOS archive). You must also specify -amiga-align on the command line if
you are calling OS functions.
Any questions you have concerning Vbcc will be answered quickly on this list
as Volker reads it and several people here use vbcc.
