The only advantage to keeping things synced with the VBlank interrupt is
that it should stop the hack interfering too badly with the multiplexing
drivers for Punchinello-II and EZMouse.

I've been giving some thought to the best way of tackling this project - and
if it were /my/ project, I think what I'd do is the following:
Try and locate the gameport.device interrupt, copy its is_Code and is_Data
fields into a fresh interrupt.
Create a new VBlank interrupt, which would signal a high-priority task.
On receipt of the signal, the task would use timer.device to wait for
about 10ms (half a VBlank) and then Cause() the duplicate interrupt.

This should trick gameport.device into sampling the mouse counters 100
times a second, but remains synchronous with AGA's VBlanks, hence
(hopefully) avoiding clashes with EZMouse/P-II drivers.

Does this make any sort of sense? ;-)

