Well, the source of my benchmark was attached. But anyway:

#include <proto/exec.h>
...
CopyMem(src, dst, size);

You can also use CopyMemQuick(), but please read the description (from
Exec.Doc):

    CopyMemQuick is a highly optimized memory copy function, with
    restrictions on the size and alignment of its arguments. Both the
    source and destination pointers must be longword aligned.  In
    addition, the size must be an integral number of longwords (e.g.
    the size must be evenly divisible by four).

    Arbitrary overlapping copies are not supported.

Btw: the later also applies to CopyMem().

Also, here CopyMem() and CopyMemQuick() is the same speed, presumably
because CopyMem() checks for hte above restrictions and call
CopyMemQuick() if possible (as it is in my benchmark).

> Well, I'm creating paralax scrolling with blocks over a background,
> with moving soft-sprites onscreen, so scrolling with the c2p would
> mean that everything else would have to be offset to get it right.

But if scrolling is what takes the most time then wouldn't it be worth
it?

It would be really nice if you'd provide the entire source and/or the
executable for better understanding of the assignment.  Though without
understanding the full process then it sounds like you're doing this:

   1) draw background
   2) draw sprites
   3) chunky to planar
   4) remove sprites
   5) scroll background
   6) go to step 2

If so then I'd assume it could be a little faster by doing something
like this:

   1) draw background into an own buffer (wider than screen)
   2) copy from background buffer to chunky buffer (with appropriate
                                                    offset for scroll)
   3) if scrolled == (e.g.) 16
      3a) switch background & chunky buffer pointers and make c2p take
                                         the offset into considuration
   3) draw sprites
   4) chunky to planar
   5) go to step 2

As I see it, you don't have to restore the background where sprites have
been and since the scroll has changed to a buffer copy then you may be
able to do this with one big mem copy, rather than a small pr. scanline
(and make the c2p mask out the extra bytes).

Regards Allan


