I  don't  see  where  the  problem  lies with using ULONG, USHORT, etc.  If
anything, it makes porting easier.

For  example,  if  you  use int (directly, with no typedef shielding), then
you'll  get differing bit widths on different machines; in the case of int,
16bit  with  Amiga,  64bit on a Cray!  As I'm sure we can all imagine, this
causes no end of bother if we're hoping for a 32 bit wide integer space and
only get 16 bits.

If  you  use  ULONGs  (etc.)  then  you  can shield the underlying type and
re-typedef   it   as   and   when   the  need  arises.   Much  better  than
search/replacing hundreds of pages of source.

The  absolutely  bestest  way of ensuring portability though, is to use the
C99 exact width data types (defined in machine/types.h).  For example

    int32_t        signed 32 bit
    u_int64_t    unsigned 64 bit
    int8_t        signed 8 bit

etc...


