Aztec-C Compiler uses 16 bit ints by default, although it can be
changed to 32 bits by using the -L  (lattice) option...

>  In the end I agree with you: I always avoid BOOL since most
> compilers generate better code if faced with 32bit entities.

I have to be the devils advocate here,  BOOL by definition requires
a storage range of 0 or 1 being a BOOLean value,
a single BYTE would be suitable....  
So it really doesn't matter if they are 8, 16, 32 or 64 bit in size.

However, I personally believe that 'int'  should be *totally* elliminated 
from C language forever, as it's size can change without notice & when
I see coders writing things like:  "int WindowPtr"   it makes my 
skin crawl.  The "ints" are the things that make programs incompatible
as when you use: BYTE, WORD,  LONG  their size is uniformly 
defined & their range is widely known, so coders clearly understand 
the wrap-around point.

Things like:   int x;    for(x=0; x < EOF; x++)
can cause hideous errors depending on external things like file size,
this is going to be even worse when you don't know how big your
ints are,  so, 32 bit ints will certainly help, but just because YOUR 
compiler defaults to 32 bit, there is no rule to say that they 
can't be 8 bits in size.     There the problem lies... 

If you use UWORD x;   you know automatically that you can
at least have 65000 records before disaster hits,  
the size of  "ints"  cannot be guaranteed.

The size of pointers on the other hand, should never be assumed
incase it gets ported to a platform with more than 4 gig of 
address space,  in that event, I would *assume* they would declare 
their pointers to be 64 bit in size,  but you get my drift..

PS:  I NEVER use ints,  Never have, never will....     
 
