@NODE "Mail_139" " Optimizing layer scroll (was: Exe + full source online :) "
From: Allan Odgaard <Duff@DIKU.DK>
Date: 10-14-00 12:31:00
Subject: @{b}Optimizing layer scroll (was: Exe + full source online :)@{ub}

On 13-Oct-00, Andrew Crowe wrote:

> I'm afraid at the moment it uses an AGA Pal screen, so if you've a gfx
> card I'm afraid you'll have to dig out that old TV :)

My PIV has a build-in scandoubler ;-)

> It features 3 independat scroll layers, and on my 040/25 amiga runs
> 25-15fps ;)

The number in the top left corner always said 21 (040/40MHz).
This was also after changing many things in the source (including the
removal of layer 2 & 3) -- maybe it's because c2p is what takes the
time, and perhaps block-selection (which is also why it's faster on
your A1200, since chipmem access is faster there), if we get a little
optimistic then you need to move 320x200 (64000) bytes pr. scroll, and
each move requires one instruction, which (on the 68040) can be
initiated every cycle, so if we forget the loop overhead and potential
dependency, cache miss and resource hazards then it's 64000 cycles to
move the screen, and we have 0.8 million of them every frame, so in
other words, maybe the scroll isn't the bottleneck, at least not on
68040/60.

> Well, unrolling the loops made a 2 to 3 times speed improvement :)

One thing to keep in mind is that the for-loop adds much overhead to a
loop, doing "while(--len >= 0)" should only give one instruction of
overhead, namely 'dbra'. If you can keep the loop at one line (plus
dbra) then you'll activate the special loop-mode of the 68010+.  I Once
had a loop consisting of two instructions which I then changed to two
separate loops (with one instruction in each) and this turned out to be
noticeable faster.  I think similar can be done with your code!

> I'm afraid b++ = a++ doesn't work:

There should have been an asterik infront of each (which the
syntax-highlight killed -- press amiga-t). But why didn't you just test
the Lib.c-source which I attached? I had done several modifications!

> Also, looking at storms ASM output, b[x]=a[x] only takes one move.b
> command, so would incrementing them instead of using fixed numbers be
> faster?

Yes, AFAIK indexed instructions (e.g. "move.b 10(a0,d0),10(a1,d0)") are
slower than non-indexed instructions (e.g. "move.b (a0),(a1)") on
the 68020/40.  And you furthermore save one add-instruction in each
iteration of the loop.

However, I don't have any written information about clock cycles etc.
for the 680x0 family (so I'm relying on my memory) -- if anyone can
provide a link (preferably also describing pipeline dependencies etc.
for the 68040/60) then I'd be very happy :-)

Regards Allan


