@NODE "Mail_149" " Loop unrolling (memcpy) "
From: Allan Odgaard <Duff@DIKU.DK>
Date: 10-15-00 11:35:18
Subject: @{b}Loop unrolling (memcpy)@{ub}

For what it's worth I did some tests with loop unrolling.

I copied 20 KB using this loop:

.loop   move.l   (a0)+,(a1)+
        dbra     d7,.loop

I tried various forms of unrulling (16 times), but the time was
completely unaffected (measured in scanlines). So I tried to calculate
the cycles spent pr. word copy (assuming a PAL screen has 290
scanlines, I might be a little wrong here) -- this gave ~10 cycles pr.
word copy.  This is quite bad considering that only one instruction is
required, so it must be the actual memory fetch which is the
bottle-neck, to test this theori I inserted two (redundant) "or.l
d3,d3" instructions in the loop, and the time was still unaffected, as
the time previously used for memory stalls could now be used to do
redundant ORs. I inserted a third one, but then the performance dropped
a little (7%).

These tests were done on a A4000 with a 40MHz 68040 MK-II card.

Regards Allan


