Hi Lee,

On Sat, 14 Oct 2000, Lee Atkins wrote:

> Hello,
> I have an array of 100 bytes and I want to shuffle these bytes into a random
> order, kind of like shuffling a deck of cards.
> I have written a routine which shuffles them but it is poor and slow.  Are
> there any known algorithms for shuffling, like qsort only qunsort ?
> 
> 

Here's two methods I've used in the past:

1)  Pick two random numbers that are indexes into your array.  Swap those
two values in the array.  Repeat some large number of times to get good
randomness.  I don't recall exactly how many times I used, but I think it
was something like 2 to 5 times the number of items to shuffle.  (As I
recall, I used a random value for the number of swaps as well, offset to
some minimum number).  If you are just using simple numbers or pointers in
the array, this is pretty quick for relatively small arrays.  (after all,
doing something like this 500 times isn't going to take that long, even on
a slowish machine)

2) If you're willing to make a copy of the array, another method I've used
is to pick a random entry from the source array and move it into the next
slot in the copy.  As the new array is built it will have a random order
relative to the original.   The hard part with this approach is dealing
with values you've already picked.  If I remember properly, I just copied
the rest of the array down to fill in the hole and reduced the maximum
random number each time.  The slow part of this is copying the array
around to fill in the hole, but with small arrays, it's not bad and you
only have to make one pass through the array (though you could do it
multiple times if you wanted).  This probably isn't the best approach, but
I thought I'd throw it out there anyhow.  Personally, I was using a small
array (52 items. :-) so it worked well for me.  If you know your pointers,
you can write a quick memcpy() type routine to move the array around,
rather than doing it piecewise (I think memcpy()'s behaviour is undefined
when the memory areas overlap, which is why I mention writing your own)

If you're interested, I can probably dig up the code to one of these and
send you a snippet.  Can't promise which one I'll find, though I'm
guessing it's the first.

Hope this provides some additional insight,
Greg

