On Sat, 14 Oct 2000, Lee Atkins wrote:

> I have an array of 100 bytes and I want to shuffle these bytes into a random
> order, kind of like shuffling a deck of cards.

Do you actually want to shuffle them or do you just want to traverse
it in random exhaustive order? For the latter I normally do something
like this:

	int i = MAX_ELEMENTS:
	while(--i)
	{
		Swap(Array[i], Array[rand() % i]):
		Report(Array[i]
	}
	Report(Array[i]):


> I have written a routine which shuffles them but it is poor and slow.  Are
> there any known algorithms for shuffling, like qsort only qunsort ?

hmm... how much do you use the shuffling routine? The above runs in
O(n) time, where qsort runs in expected O(n log n) time, so trying a
divide'n'conquer approach is not a good idea... 

The bottle-neck in shuffling is most likely rand(), if you find the above
unsatisfactory then I can provide you with a faster rand() implementation.


