On Tue, 17 Oct 2000, Lee Atkins wrote:

> btw.  Theres a bloke at work that declares all his functions as statics eg.
>  static void Foo(void);
> Is there some point to this?
> 

This prevents the functions from being called from outside the current
compilation unit (module).  It can be useful if you want to make a
function "private" or to avoid function name conflicts.  However, I cannot
see any point to declaring *all* functions that way.

I'll often use something like this when writing a utility module.  I'll
declare the public interface functions as normal and put the prototypes in
a header file for that module.  For the internal "worker" functions, I'll
put the prototypes at the top of the module and declare them as static so
they cannot be called from outside the module.

Hope this explains it a bit for you.

