Subject: @{b}Accessing serial port@{ub}

Hi,

I am writing a tool to make my TI89 calculator communicate with my Amiga.
It works well now but I still have a big problem. I am directly using the
hardware adresses because I need non-standard access to serial port ( ie.
accessing to RTS/CTS/... directly ). My problem is that the TI protocol is
asynchronous, that means, for example :
- TI & computer are waiting
- TI sends info on a line of data
- Computer replies OK on the other line
- TI stop emitting
- Computer stop replying.
- Go to the beginning, for each bit.

Then, I don't know when I have to wait for a bit.
Also, when the computer sends a data, I has to wait for the 'ack'.
Those waits are my problems.

I have tested to solutions :
- active loops : works well but suck all the CPU for quite nothing.
- timer : I use timer.device and TR_ADDREQUEST. The main problems of this
solution are :
 1. I don't know how to set the time to wait.
 2. If I set a fixed time, then I am not sure to have the maximal transfer
rate at each moment.
 3. If the waiting time is not fixed, then I have to find good values, or to
test the data line X time, with T microsec between each. But then I have
the problem of the active loops.
 4. The waiting time are in the range 1-100microsecs, and this time seems to
be too little for the timer.device : I wonder even if the time to call the
OS function is not already more than 1microsec.

I'm thinking about creating two tasks :
- one waiting for data transfer, with an active loop, and priority -128
- the other, catching and analysing the datas.

Do you think this would be a good idea ? I'm not totally convinced, it looks
dirty.

Perhaps is there any exception based solution ? Then I would be happy to
learn more.


Thanks


Olivier Croquette


