>From: Jack York <jyork@voyager.net>

>I have a linked list of items using the struct
>typedef struct mystruct
>{
>     struct Node nn_Node;
>     TEXT          name[50];
>} mystruct;
>
>When I do the following the list is printed without a problem.
>mystruct *m;
>
>for (m = (mystruct *)list->lh_Head; m->nn_Node.ln_Succ;
>        m = (mystruct *)m->nn_Node.ln_Succ)
>  puts(m->name);
>
>But if I do the following I get an extra line of garbage
>printed at the end of the list.  I never see the "this is the last
>entry" statement.  Can someone explain where the
>problem is at?

The (good) thing about Exec lists is that they are doubly linked, and the 
last node in a list also points to the list structure itself, so your loop 
checking the "ln_Succ" field in the last node is actually finding a pointer 
back to the list itself, and not a NULL.

You need to do this instead:

struct mystruct
{
     struct Node nn_Node;
     TEXT          name[50];
}list;

mystruct *m;

// first assign m to the head of the list
m=(mystruct*)list.mn_Node.lh_Head;

// then loop around it
while(m->mn_Node.lh_Head)
{
   puts(m->name);
   m=(mystruct*)m->mn_Node.lh_Head;
}

Hope this helps.

Andrew Markwell





