@NODE "Mail_265" " Variable declarations (was: Re: Fails on looping list) "
From: Allan Odgaard <Duff@DIKU.DK>
Date: 10-29-00 01:02:23
Subject: @{b}Variable declarations (was: Re: Fails on looping list)@{ub}

On 28-Oct-00, Jack York wrote:

>> Btw: it might make the code more readable if you settle with
>> typecasting in the body of the loop, i.e.:
> I always thought anything not needed for each pass in a loop should be
> taken out for better code. [...] does this not apply [...]

hmm... that spawns several answers:

Normally a construction like: "MyType a = (MyType)b;" doesn't create an
_actual_ new variable, i.e. the compiler will use the same register for
both variables, because they are in fact the same -- but while
compiling, the type checker will use the extra information.

Furthermore, the 3 statements in your for(;;)-construction are part of
the loop body. So it wouldn't really change things.

And finally, a good compiler will move variable declarations outside a
loop body, if possible. So you shouldn't worry about these things, your
worries should be about keeping the source readable and maintainable,
and here I'd argue that one should put a variable declaration as close
as possible to its actual use -- remember those old ANSI-C sources
which starts by 20-40 variable declarations? ;-)

Regards Allan


